  "prompt": "Can I glue a tooth filling back into my mouth?",
  "response": "**No, you should not attempt to glue a tooth filling back into your mouth yourself.** This is **not safe** and can lead to serious problems. Here's why:\n\n*   **Hygiene:** Your mouth is full of bacteria. Trying to reattach a filling yourself without proper sterilization will introduce bacteria into the cavity, increasing the risk of infection and further decay.\n*   **Proper Fit:** The filling needs to fit perfectly to seal the cavity and prevent bacteria from entering. You cannot achieve this level of precision at home. Even if it seems to fit, there might be microscopic gaps.\n*   **Correct Materials:** Over-the-counter adhesives are not designed for use in the mouth. They can be toxic if ingested, may not bond properly to the tooth, and can dissolve in saliva, creating a breeding ground for bacteria.\n*   **Damage:** Attempting to force a filling back into place could damage the tooth or surrounding tissues.\n\n**What you should do:**\n\n1.  **Contact your dentist immediately.** Explain the situation and ask for an appointment as soon as possible. A lost filling exposes the tooth to decay and can cause sensitivity or pain.\n2.  **Pain Relief:** If you're experiencing pain, you can take over-the-counter pain relievers like ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin) or acetaminophen (Tylenol).\n3.  **Temporary Protection:** While waiting for your dental appointment, you can try the following to protect the exposed tooth:\n    *   **Temporary Filling Material:** Pharmacies often sell temporary filling kits. These are designed to provide a temporary seal and are a better option than household glue. Follow the package instructions carefully.\n    *   **Sugar-Free Gum:** If you don't have a temporary filling material, you can use a small piece of sugar-free gum to cover the exposed area, especially before eating.\n4.  **Oral Hygiene:** Continue to brush and floss gently around the affected tooth. You might want to use a soft-bristled toothbrush.\n\n**In summary, see your dentist as soon as possible. Do not attempt to reattach the filling yourself with glue or any other household product.**\n",
